<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,313,324,348]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" reason="1">Variation.</emphasis>
The species is represented by two wing pattern forms. More typical form is dark with little white suffusion distally from reniform (
<figureCitation box="[510,680,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1824,1848]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,220,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-77@1.[151,1436,220,1780]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Anepholcia spp., imagines. 1. A rosahoferae sp. n., HT male, Nepal, genit. prep. 8070GB; 2. Ditto, PT, underside; 3. Ditto, PT, male, white form, genit. prep. 8067GB; 4. A. pygaria, male, Vietnam; 5, 6—A. pygaria 5—male, 6—female; 7–20. Type series of A. rosahoferae sp. n. (7— holotype, 8–20—paratypes; 7–16—dark form; 17–20—pale form)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276651/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Figs. 1, 2, 7–16</figureCitation>
) Four specimens of the 
<typeStatus box="[941,987,360,383]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">type</typeStatus>
series (
<figureCitation box="[1070,1199,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1824,1848]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,220,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-77@1.[151,1436,220,1780]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Anepholcia spp., imagines. 1. A rosahoferae sp. n., HT male, Nepal, genit. prep. 8070GB; 2. Ditto, PT, underside; 3. Ditto, PT, male, white form, genit. prep. 8067GB; 4. A. pygaria, male, Vietnam; 5, 6—A. pygaria 5—male, 6—female; 7–20. Type series of A. rosahoferae sp. n. (7— holotype, 8–20—paratypes; 7–16—dark form; 17–20—pale form)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276651/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Figs. 17–20</figureCitation>
) show pale form with intensive white suffusion on forewing outward of reniform and medial shadow, resembling females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1263,1377,394,417]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygaria">
<emphasis box="[1263,1377,394,417]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">A. pygaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–20" captionStartId="1.[151,269,1824,1848]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,220,1770]" captionTargetId="figure-77@1.[151,1436,220,1780]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–20. Anepholcia spp., imagines. 1. A rosahoferae sp. n., HT male, Nepal, genit. prep. 8070GB; 2. Ditto, PT, underside; 3. Ditto, PT, male, white form, genit. prep. 8067GB; 4. A. pygaria, male, Vietnam; 5, 6—A. pygaria 5—male, 6—female; 7–20. Type series of A. rosahoferae sp. n. (7— holotype, 8–20—paratypes; 7–16—dark form; 17–20—pale form)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276651" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276651/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). The male genitalia of both forms are identical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis box="[199,415,463,487]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,463,487]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[321,402,464,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–22" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[321,1400,223,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-117@2.[151,1436,194,1754]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 21–22. Anepholcia spp., male genitalia. 21—A rosahoferae sp. n., HT, Nepal, genit. prep. 8070GB; 22—A. pygaria, Vietnam, genit. prep. 7923GB." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276653" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276653/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Male. Uncus shorter and broader than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[877,992,464,487]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygaria">
<emphasis box="[877,992,464,487]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">A. pygaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1009,1091,464,487]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–22" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionTargetBox="[321,1400,223,1721]" captionTargetId="figure-117@2.[151,1436,194,1754]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 21–22. Anepholcia spp., male genitalia. 21—A rosahoferae sp. n., HT, Nepal, genit. prep. 8070GB; 22—A. pygaria, Vietnam, genit. prep. 7923GB." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5276653" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5276653/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), spatulate, somewhat extended subapically, with rounded apex; tegumen with very wide lobes bearing short tooth-like lateral extensions, shorter than vinculum; juxta triangular, huge, shield-like, with small central bar; valva with parallel margins on half of length, from tip of sacculus constricted apically, longer and more extended than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[931,1047,568,591]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygaria">
<emphasis box="[931,1047,568,591]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">A. pygaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; costa and ventral margin of valva heavily sclerotised, cucullus apically rounded, covered with strong setae, covering about half of costa; central part of valva with large sclerotised plate extending from costa and large editum; sacculus rather broad, clavus not expressed, clasper with strong short tooth-extension, shorter than in other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Prout" authorityYear="1922" box="[993,1114,672,695]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[993,1114,672,695]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Anepholcia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; vinculum V-like. Aedeagus straight, rather long, strong, carina with numerous short spines apically; vesica projecting dorsally, significantly extended medially, with two pouch-like subbasal diverticula larger than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[901,1020,741,764]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygaria">
<emphasis box="[901,1020,741,764]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">A. pygaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and with large and broad subapical diverticulum. Female: unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="62" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis box="[199,345,810,834]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,810,834]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Distribution</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The species is known only from the type-locality in Central 
<collectingCountry box="[995,1061,810,833]" name="Nepal" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, far away from known localities of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Warren" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[151,263,845,868]" class="Insecta" family="Pantheidae" genus="Anepholcia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pygaria">
<emphasis box="[151,263,845,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">A. pygaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in Northern 
<collectingCountry box="[398,493,845,868]" name="Thailand" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[544,650,845,868]" name="Myanmar" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
. The species inhabits mid mountain belt at elevation 
<quantity box="[1211,1293,845,868]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.7" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" unit="m" value="2700.0">2700 m</quantity>
, flight period – July.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="62" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,914,938]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is named in honor of Ms. Rosa Hofer, the wife of the enthusiastic Austrian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1307,1435,914,937]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="62" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
collector Franz Hofer, who presented us the material for the description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
